By following individually a subsample of 423 wetlands, we analyzed wetland-drying frequency as an indicator of wetland vulnerability over the last 30 years. Among the eight variables included in our GLM analysis, %GCC (Likelihood ratio test = 4.7, p = 0.02; 
 Table 2; 
 Fig 7A) and wetland shape index (SI; Likelihood ratio test = 13.1, p < 0.001; 
 Table 2; 
 Fig 7C) were the only single variables that significantly affected wetland drying rate over the last 30 years: round wetlands and those located in highly glacierized catchments were less prone to drying. While the ‘initial area of wetland’ was not significant in the GLM (see 
 Table 2, 
 Fig 7B), its interaction with SI was by far the most significant term affecting wetland drying over the last 30 years (LRT = 48.4, p < 0.0001; 
 Table 2). Relatively small wetlands with high shape index (SI) values, 
 i.
